Behind me, we have several examples of how dialogs work in this module.  It is a script-based system based on zz-dialog and and customized by squattingmonk.

Click on each NPC or other object to see the system in action.

This NPC is demonstrating a simple dynamic dialog. To make this happen, we:

1. Set his  conversation to "dlg_conv_zoom" (or "dlg_conv_nozoom" if we don't want to zoom in).

2. Add a string variable named "*Dialog" with the value "PoetDialog".

3. Say, "Wow, that was easy!"

Speaking with this young man will start a conversation which demonstrates the use of tokens within a dialog.  As long as the dialog is created with our custom dialog system, these tokens can be inserted directly into the text and will be evaluated at run time.

To make this happen, within a dialog page's text string, insert the appropriate token, such as <lady/lord>.  When the system encounters this token, the token will be evaluated based on the PC's gender and the appropriate option will be displayed.

Pulling this lever to see the various colors you can use in your dialogs, messages and other areas of the module.  To make this happen, we:

1. Add "#include util_i_color" to the top of the script.

2. Call one of the text coloring functions, such as HexColor(), RGBColor(), HSVColor(), etc. depending on the color value you want to set.  In this example, all text is colored using constants send to the HexToColor() function.

Behind me, we have several examples of how merchant conversations work in this module.  Merchant conversations are based in the dialog system examples shown in the Dialog Demo area next door.  

To have a merchant open his store using the standard conversation, simply accomplish these steps:

1. Create the NPC shopowner, set their conversation to "dlg_convzoom" and set the string variable "*Dialog" to "MerchantDialog".

2. Create a merchant waypoint (store).  If the shopowner NPC will be static (not walking around), simply place the store waypoint directly underneat the shopowner NPC and the script will find it when the PC chooses to open the store.  If the shopowner will not be static or will not be co-located with his store, set a string variable "*Store" to the tag of the merchant/store waypoint.  This feature allows stores be located in a central repository/inaccessable while still allowing simple merchant creation without scripting.

This merchant demonstrates a static merchant who opens their store based on a conversation and a store waypoint, but only opens the store to male characters.  Although invisible while playing, the merchant/store waypoint is directly underneath this NPC.  This allows the conversation script to find this NPC's store without any additonal scripting.

To make this happen, we:

1. Created the NPC
2. Created the store
3. Added the string variable "*Dialog* to the NPC with a value of "MerchantDialog"
4. Placed the NPC on the merchant waypoint.
5. Modified the dialog script to check for a specific characteristic.
This sturdy blacksmith's anvil bears the dented sheen of long use. Something in you wonders what great weapons and armor have been shaped upon its well-worn surface.

Clicking on this anvil will show a demonstration that conversations can be used for placeables and other objects, not just NPCs.  The conversation associated with this anvil will allow the PC to copy or delete items in their inventory.  It dynamically reads the players inventory, creates conversation nodes to allow the PC to copy or delete a specific object in their inventory, and then modifies the player's inventory appropriately.

Unlike the NPCs, however, we are using a variable to start the conversation instead of the conversation setting.  For this anvil, you will find the standard "*Dialog" variable set, but there is another string variable called "OnPlaceableUsed" set to "StartDialog".  This directs the event management system to run the "StartDialog" library script when a PC interacts with this object.

Using an event variable is one of the many way to manage events in the module.

Behind me is The Shape Shifter.  He is responsible for creating, modifying, moving and destroying custom shapes.  For now, he'll jsut do what he wants, but you can talk to him to get him to do something special, if he's feeling up to it.

Just a few words on event management.  The framework system installed in this module has many different way to assign scripts to an event.  They can be assigned through library script exposure, assigning scripts to specific events in object variables, assigned an object with scripts loaded to another object, carrying scripts on the PC to be used in whatever area they are in and loading event variables and script names dynamically.

You can even turn event scripts on and off dynamically, in case you want to, for example, have an area exit event fire for every area in the module, except for one or two.  Event can also fire locally, such as only on a specific area or other object.

Behind me lies the Bat Cav ... er, the module Data Center.  It holds what is generally considered a DM only area with visualizations of the module datapoints.  This area may also contain waypoint, items and other objects that normal PCs should not have access to.  This area is currently CLOSED UFN.

You may notice some random, half-naked NPCs running arund this area, seemingly appearing out of nowhere, walking around for a bit and then disappearing.  This is the module's crowd system at work.  It's designed to make the cities and other areas where it's assigned to look more alive and bustling with activity as any city would.

It can be used by accomplishing these tasks (in addition to creating the NPCs that will be walking around the clothing they will wear):
1 . Create a "crowd initializer item" by editing a COPY of the "crowd_template" item listed under Special -> Custom 2.  Your new items must start with "crowd_".  Upon creation of the new item, on the "General Tab", rename the Item Name, Tag and Blueprint ResRef to the new name of your item.  So if you're creating a crowd to handle Kleg Town Guards, all three values should be changed to "crowd_kregguard".  There is a 16 character limit for these names.

2. On the "Description" tab, click on "Variables" and set the variables to the values you wish to use for your crowd. Areas can have multiple crowds with different settings.  If you want to use default (safe) settings, you can even delete variables from this list, but it is not a best-practice to do so.  The variables are generally self-explanatory.

3. Drop waypoints where you want the crowd members to spawn and walk to.  Use normal, boring waypoints. The tag of the waypoint must match the Waypoint_Tag you set in the variables list.  Each crown will use their designated waypoints, so you can set up a different "patrol route" for each crowd.

4. Set a string variable called "*Crowds" on the area where the crowd is to be created.  Set this variable to the name of your crowd initializer item without the "crowd_" prefix.  So if you are creating an crowd based on "crowd_KregGuard", This variable shold be set to "KregGuard".  If you have multiple crowds based on multiple items, the variable can be a string-delimited list.  If you are creating citizens in Kreg and a Guard in Kreg, you must create two different initializer items, but the area variable "*Crowds" will be set to "KregGuard,KregCitizens" or something similar.

This start area serves several purposes.  Although it will likely never see a production server, it is currently being used to showcase the various systems that are installed in the server.  So feel free to look around and discover what's here!
Dark Sun uses a custom quest system that handles all aspects of quest assignment and completion.  Talk to the NPC to the right of this sign to see an example of several quest types in action!
